data.text: @gnavas103 Yeah that’s the only good thing about this storm is it’s small. That also allows other factors to effect it more noticeably, which could be part of the problem tracking it
@IanHest Its a tiny storm comparative to most hurricanes, so ANY interaction with land will break up up really fast

However, the slower the storm means longer periods of heavy rain. That introduces a flooding aspect for coastal FL that wouldn’t be present with a fast moving storm slamming in the state and passing through

This is from @bamwxcom based on the Euro ensemble models. The storm is slowing down, so possibly take this “cone”/track and shift it East. Slight Possibility of little to no landfall in FL https://t.co/T6duXJ7xGP
For the first time in my life, I’m rooting against a small hurricane coming our way. We have the whole Thanksgiving Week off if we don’t have to miss school because of this storm. I hate getting old.

So here’s what I recommend doing today: if you’re anywhere from Miami to Melbourne, get your supplies ready today, don’t wait because I’m sure there’s already a rush and the weekend will be nuts. Keep an eye on the storm throughout today and tonight but don’t stress it

One really good thing about this storm though is, it’s small. The hurricane and TS force winds don’t extend very far out from center. Also because of the size, it will break up very quickly upon landfall. The bad part is it’s teetering on Cat 4 landfall
